      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The age-old problem of team dynamics, much like a group of goblins fighting over a treasure hoard. You see, just as a goblin might try to steal the treasure from his own kin, these team members are undermining each other's efforts. It's essential to address this issue before it's too late, or your team's progress will be as slow as a goblin navigating a dark cave without a map.\n\nTo tackle this, I recommend having a private meeting with each of the team members involved. Ask them to share their perspective on the situation, and listen actively, just as a goblin might listen for the sound of approaching guards. This will help you understand their motivations and concerns, and you can work together to find a solution.\n\nNext, consider setting clear expectations for team behavior and communication during meetings. You might say something like, \"Just as a goblin works together with his tribe to achieve a common goal, we need to support each other in our work.\" This will help reinforce the importance of collaboration and respect.\n\nFinally, consider implementing a \"no undermining\" policy, where team members are encouraged to focus on their own tasks and avoid criticizing or belittling their colleagues. You can also establish a \"goblin-free",
